</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[885,1009,1773,1798]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="mikacae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[885,1009,1773,1798]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P. mikacae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1019,1085,1773,1798]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1019,1085,1773,1798]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[1102,1211,1774,1797]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="moorei" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1102,1211,1774,1797]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P. moorei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1221,1287,1773,1798]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1221,1287,1773,1798]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Johnson, 1901)" authorityName="NE" baseAuthorityName="Johnson" baseAuthorityYear="1901" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="papillata">
<emphasis box="[1304,1435,1773,1798]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P. papillata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Johnson, H. P." box="[158,327,1809,1834]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="381 - 437" refId="ref48634" refString="Johnson, H. P. (1901) The Polychaeta of the Puget Sound region. Proceedings of the Boston Society of Natural History, 29, 381 - 437." type="journal article" year="1901">Johnson, 1901</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[401,510,1809,1834]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="rullieri">
<emphasis box="[401,510,1809,1834]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P. rullieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because they have sediment-free papillae. It has been indicated that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Leidy" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[1307,1407,1809,1834]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[1307,1407,1809,1834]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique because it has neurohooks from chaetiger 5, instead of starting from chaetiger 4 as in the other species. With falcate medial and posterior neurohooks, 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[621,758,1881,1906]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hobsonae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[621,758,1881,1906]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P. hobsonae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[765,829,1881,1906]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[765,829,1881,1906]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is more similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[1047,1169,1881,1906]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="mikacae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1047,1169,1881,1906]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P. mikacae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1178,1242,1881,1906]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1178,1242,1881,1906]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="NE" baseAuthorityName="Johnson" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[1299,1429,1881,1906]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="papillata">
<emphasis box="[1299,1429,1881,1906]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P. papillata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2014" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[268,404,1917,1942]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hobsonae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[268,404,1917,1942]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P. hobsonae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[413,477,1917,1942]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[413,477,1917,1942]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be easily distinguished as it has only 2–3 transverse series of papillae, and 2–3 neurochaetae in medial chaetigers, whereas the other two species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[916,1039,1953,1978]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="mikacae">
<emphasis box="[916,1039,1953,1978]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P. mikacae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="NE" baseAuthorityName="Johnson" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[1098,1229,1953,1978]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="papillata">
<emphasis box="[1098,1229,1953,1978]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P. papillata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, have 10 or more transverse series of papillae, and 3–5 neurohooks.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
The reduction in the number of transverse series of papillae is unexpected in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Oken" authorityYear="1807" box="[1079,1172,151,176]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1079,1172,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Pherusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but this is common in 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamberlin, 1919" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1919" box="[151,487,188,213]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Semiodera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,271,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Semiodera</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Chamberlin, R. V." box="[281,487,188,213]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 514" refId="ref46587" refString="Chamberlin, R. V. (1919) The Annelida Polychaeta of the Albatross Tropical Pacific Expedition, 1891 - 1905. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard College, 48, 1 - 514. Available from: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / bibliography / 49195  / summary (Accessed 1 Nov. 2014)" type="journal article" year="1919">Chamberlin, 1919</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Salazar-Vallejo, S. I." box="[505,761,188,213]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 62" refId="ref50785" refString="Salazar-Vallejo, S. I. (2012 c) Revison of Semiodera Chamberlin, 1919 (Polychaeta: Flabelligeridae). Zootaxa, 3562, 1 - 62." type="journal article" year="2012">Salazar-Vallejo 2012c</bibRefCitation>
). The latter includes species with a dorsal shield made of cemented sediment particles, and in comparison to 
<taxonomicName box="[724,907,223,248]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[724,817,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Pherusa</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, their papillae are reduced in size; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Oken" authorityYear="1807" box="[1295,1388,223,248]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1295,1388,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Pherusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1919" box="[151,271,260,285]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Semiodera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,271,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Semiodera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also differ in the number of transverse rows of papillae per segment. Most 
<taxonomicName box="[1164,1375,260,285]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Semiodera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1164,1284,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Semiodera</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
bore calcareous substrates or consolidated muds (pers. obs.), where they build galleries and only expose their long cephalic cage or occasionally the posterior end for defecation. Their body sometimes resembles sabellariids by having a long, thin posterior region for this purpose. Regretfully, there is no further information about the ecology of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2014" box="[181,316,404,429]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Pherusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hobsonae">
<emphasis box="[181,316,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">P. hobsonae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; because of reductions in papillae size and number of transverse rows, it can be hypothesized that it lives in rocky shore interstices. The broken cephalic cage might indicate that the specimens were gathered by breaking rocks. The possibility that members of the species actually bore into calcareous substrates, or even only furnish a gallery inside them, deserves closer study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1351,548,573]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,151,573]" box="[199,1351,548,573]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,548,573]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Distribution</emphasis>
. Only known from the 
<typeStatus box="[608,656,548,572]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">type</typeStatus>
locality, probably living in intertidal rocky or mixed bottoms.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
